pzl: lsr hfx nvd
qnr: nvd
ntq: jqt hfx bvb xhk
nvd: lhk
lsr: lhk
rzs: qnr cmg lsr rsh
frs: qnr lhk lsr
}\if{html}{\out{</div>}}

Each line shows the \emph{name of a component}, a colon, and then \emph{a list of
other components} to which that component is connected. Connections
aren\'t directional; \code{abc: xyz} and \code{xyz: abc} both represent the same
configuration. Each connection between two components is represented
only once, so some components might only ever appear on the left or
right side of a colon.

In this example, if you disconnect the wire between \code{hfx}/\code{pzl}, the
wire between \code{bvb}/\code{cmg}, and the wire between \code{nvd}/\code{jqt}, you will
\emph{divide the components into two separate, disconnected groups}:
\itemize{
\item \emph{\code{9}} components: \code{cmg}, \code{frs}, \code{lhk}, \code{lsr}, \code{nvd}, \code{pzl}, \code{qnr},
